On November 20, 2018, President Donald J. Trump issued a proclamation declaring Thursday, November 22, 2018, as a National Day of Thanksgiving. The proclamation reflects on the journey of the Pilgrims who came to America to escape religious persecution and establish a home in the New World. It emphasizes the Pilgrims' faith in God and their gratitude for His mercy and blessings. The proclamation also mentions how President George Washington and President Abraham Lincoln revived the tradition of Thanksgiving, and encourages Americans to reflect on their heritage and the sacrifices of their forebearers. President Trump calls on Americans to gather with family and friends, to give thanks, and to extend generosity and compassion to those in need. The proclamation acknowledges the sacrifices of service members, law enforcement personnel, and first responders who are away from their loved ones during the holiday. It concludes by urging Americans to offer a prayer of thanks to God for their blessings.